Step 1: #Configure Git (one-time setup)

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your-email@example.com"

Step 2: #Create a Local Project Directory

mkdir git-local-remote  #repo name can give any name
cd git-local-remote 

Step 3: #Initialize Git in the Directory
git init

Step 4: #Add Files and Commit

echo "# git-local-remote" > README.md
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"

Step 5: #Create and Push to GitHub Using GitHub CLI

gh repo create git-local-remote --public --source=. --remote=origin --push

ðŸ”¹ This command does the following:

Creates a public repo on GitHub
Links your local repo to the remote (origin)
Pushes your code to GitHub
